{"id":"1510.06508","submitter":"Martin Virte","authors":"Martin Virte","title":"Noise induced stabilization of chaotic free-running laser diode","comments":"accepted manuscript in Chaos: An interdisciplinary journal of\n  Nonlinear Science, 8 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":"Chaos 26, 053108 (2016)","doi":"10.1063/1.4951682","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.optics nlin.CD","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper, we investigate theoretically the stabilization of a\nfree-running vertical-cavity surface-emitting laser exhibiting polarization\nchaos dynamics. We report the existence of a boundary isolating the chaotic\nattractor on one side and a steady-state on the other side, and identify the\nunstable periodic orbit playing the role of separatrix. In addition, we\nhighlight a small range of parameters where the chaotic attractor passes\nthrough this boundary, and therefore where chaos only appears as a transient\nbehaviour. Then, including the effect of spontaneous emission noise in the\nlaser, we demonstrate that, for realistic levels of noise, the system is\nsystematically pushed over the separating solution. As a result, we show that\nthe chaotic dynamics cannot be sustained unless the steady-state on the other\nside of the separatrix becomes unstable. Finally, we link the stability of this\nsteady-state to a small value of the birefringence in the laser cavity and\ndiscuss the significance of this result on future experimental work.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 22 Oct 2015 07:46:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 2 Jan 2016 17:10:21 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 12 May 2016 12:39:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-05-26"}
